notransferase","Total bilirubin","Albumin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most liver-specific enzyme in liver function tests. In contrast to aspartate aminotransferase (AST), which is found in both the cytoplasm and mitochondria, ALT is found exclusively in the cytoplasm. \u003Cstrong\u003EAspartate aminotransferase (AST)\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the liver, cardiac muscle, skeletal muscle, kidneys, brain, pancreas, lungs, leukocytes, and red cells. Consequently, it is less sensitive or specific to the liver than ALT. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme found throughout the body, but it is mostly found in the liver, bones, kidneys, and digestive system. When the liver is damaged, ALP may leak into the bloodstream. High levels of ALP can indicate liver disease or bone disorders. High levels of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E may indicate liver damage or disease. However, high levels can also be due to medications, exercise, or certain foods. Bilirubin is also a product of the breakdown of red blood cells, and an elevated reading may be related to disorders of red blood cells and not a liver disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin\u003C/strong\u003E is a protein made by the liver. Levels of albumin may decrease, to a greater or lesser degree, when conditions interfere with its production by the liver, increase protein breakdown, increase protein loss via the kidneys, and/or expand plasma volume (diluting the blood).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) is the most liver-specific enzyme in liver function tests.","Aspartate aminotransferase (AST) is less specific to the liver as it is found in multiple tissues including cardiac and skeletal muscle."],"references":["Limdi JK, Hyde GM. Evaluation of abnormal liver function tests. Postgrad Med J. 2003 Jun;79(932):307-12. doi: 10.1136/pmj.79.932.307. PMID: 12840117; PMCID: PMC1742736. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12840117/","Newsome PN, Cramb R, Davison SM, Dillon JF, Foulerton M, Godfrey EM, Hall R, Harrower U, Hudson M, Langford A, Mackie A, Mitchell-Thain R, Sennett K, Sheron NC, Verne J, Walmsley M, Yeoman A. Guidelines on the management of abnormal liver blood tests. Gut. 2018 Jan;67(1):6-19. doi: 10.1136/gutjnl-2017-314924. Epub 2017 Nov 9. PMID: 29122851; PMCID: PMC5754852. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29122851/","Lala V, Zubair M, Minter DA. Liver Function Tests. 2023 Jul 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29494096. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29494096/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63536"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:52:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:53:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4507"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ